ts of students in the landmark Tinker v. Des Moines case.A series of students’ rights lawsuits in the desegregation era challenged everything from school curricula to disciplinary policies. But in casting students as “troublemakers” or as “culturally deficient,” school authorities and other experts persuaded the courts to set limits on rights protections that made students of color disproportionately vulnerable to suspension and expulsion. Troublemakers traces the history of black and Chicano student protests from small-town Mississippi to metropolitan Denver and beyond, showcasing the stories of individual protesters and demonstrating how their actions contributed to the eventual recognition of the constitutional rights of all students. Offering a fresh interpretation of this pivotal era, Troublemakers shows that when black and Chicano teenagers challenged racial discrimination in American public schools, they helped remake American constitutional law and establish protections of free speech, due process, equal protection, and privacy for students.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aNineteen sixtiesxSocial aspects. 0aNineteen sixties-Social aspects. 0aStudentsxCivil rightszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aStudents-Civil rights-United States-History-20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aBlackwell v. Issaquena.  aBrown v. Board.  aBurnside v. Byars.  aChicano Movement.  aChildren’s Defense Fund.  aEighth Amendment.  aFirst Amendment.  aFourteenth Amendment.  aFourth Amendment.  aFreedom Summer.  aGoss v. Lopez.  aIngraham v. Wright.  aKeyes v. School District.  aMexican American.  aMississippi.  aSouthern Regional Council.  aSupreme Court.  aTinker v. Des Moines.  aUnited Nations.  abilingual education.  achildren’s rights.  acivil ri